['Meanwhile, please keep in mind that the best ways to prevent the spread of COVID-19 are: Maintain your Social Distancing – At least 6 Feet apart!
Stay at home if at all possible.
* Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.
If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer.
* Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands.
* Avoid close contact with people who are sick.
* Stay home when you are sick, or if you are a not an essential employee.
* Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then immediately throw the tissue in the trash.
* Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.
COVID-19 spreads through the air when an infected person coughs or sneezes.
Symptoms are thought to appear within two to 14 days after exposure and consist of fever, cough, runny nose, and difficulty breathing.
For people with mild illness, individuals are asked to stay home, drink plenty of fluids, and get rest.
For people with more severe symptoms, such as shortness of breath, individuals are advised to seek healthcare, using telemedicine where available.

In Dougherty County, Phoebe Putney Memorial Hospital has re- ported four deaths connected to COVID-19.
Large gatherings of individuals pose a risk of the spread of COVID-19 and the CDC recommends limiting large gatherings to contain the spread.
For the full Joint Executive Order, visit Dougherty.ga.us and the News and Events/Public Notices section.

City of Albany/Dougherty County Declaration of Disaster & Public Health Emergency FAQs When does the order go into effect?
The order goes into effect at 8 a.m. on March 20, 2020.
How long does the order last?
The order is in place for seven days (March 25, 2020).
It may be amended at any time should circumstances dictate.
Will there be enforcement and how?
A violation of the order is a misdemeanor.
If you have a complaint about businesses operating outside of the order or large community gatherings during the effective period, please notify the Emergency Operations Center at (229) 302-1900.
The City may use other enforcement tools as allowed by law.
To report a potential violation of the order, Should my business close during this time?
The order does not require all private businesses to temporarily close, but those that fall under the categories listed in the declaration of Public Health Emergency are expected to follow the order.
If you are unsure if your business falls under the classifications listed in the order, call 311.
Are daycares required to close under this order?
No.
Childcare facilities are not included in this order, but should maintain social distancing.
Can production facilities and distribution centers stay open?
Yes, production facilities and distribution centers may remain open so long as social distancing guidelines of six feet are followed.
Will grocery stores remain open?
Yes, grocery stores may remain open so long as persons are not within six feet of one another for extended periods of time.
Will retailers and shopping centers have to close?

Malls and shopping centers and other retail establishments are not included in the definition of community gathering so long as persons are not within six feet of one another for extended periods of time.
Does my church have to cancel in-person service?
Possibly.

A community gathering is defined as any indoor or outdoor event or convening that brings or is likely to bring together 10 or more persons at the same time in a single room or enclosed space including auditoriums, meeting halls and event centers.
Please see definitions in section 7 of the order.
Depending upon the size of your congregation, your in-person services may violate the order.
Can we still hold funeral services?
Yes, as long as indoor attendance is limited to less than 10 persons per the community gathering definition in sections 4 and 6 of the order.

Outdoor graveside services would not be subject to the community gathering prohibition as long as they are not in fenced or otherwise enclosed spaces and attendees are able to maintain 6-foot social distancing measures.
Can we still hold weddings, birthday parties, book clubs, baby showers, private gatherings in a home?
At a business?
Possibly.
Public or private community gatherings that bring together or are likely to bring together 10 or more people at the same time are prohibited.
Please see Sections 4 and 6 of the Order for the specific definitions or requirements.
The Mayor and Dougherty County Public Health District strongly recommend canceling, rescheduling or not attending events with more than 10 persons.
If my restaurant/bar/gym limits access to 10 members or less at a time, does it have to close?
Restaurants are prohibited from providing service in their dining rooms.
Restaurants may continue to provide drive through, pick up/curbside and delivery services.
Bars and other similar establishments are closed.
Gyms and other similar businesses fall under the temporary closure order.
My hotel has a restaurant and/or continental breakfast buffet.
Should that be closed?
Yes.
Food should be delivered to rooms or picked up to-go during the effective period of the order.
Are beauty and barber shops allowed to stay open?
Yes.
Social distancing guidelines of six feet are required.
Can dance studios continue classes that are limited to 10 students or less at one time?
No.
A dance studio falls under the category of Indoor Recreational Facility and is subject to the requirements of the order.
Can employees of businesses not affected by the order still be allowed to come in to work, but remain closed to the public?
Yes, as long as community gathering situations are not created as defined in the order (sections 5 and 7).
The recommended six-foot social distance is required.
Can we still maintain our dentist, eye doctor, and medical doctor appointments?
Yes.
Hospitals and medical facilities are not included in the Community Gathering definition so long as persons are generally not within 6 feet of one another for extended periods.

Please see the social distancing recommendations included with the order or visit https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/downloads/community-mitigation-strategy.pdf Will the City work with people who cannot pay their utility bill due to being out of work as a result of COVID-19?
If you are unable to pay your bill, please contact the the Albany Utility Board at (229) 883-8330.
As always, utilities staff is prepared to work with you on a payment plan for your bill.
Is public transit still running a full schedule?
Yes.
Transit services are not prohibited under the order and are continuing as normal, with enhanced measures for cleaning.
Six foot distancing still required.
Is the animal shelter remaining open?
Animal shelter operations are continuing as normal.
Are parks and playgrounds still open?
Outdoor recreational facilities such as parks and playgrounds remain open so long as there are not gatherings of 10 or more people.
Parks and Recreation has implemented an extensive cleaning schedule for all playground equipment, tables, benches and other outdoor facilities. ']
